<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-12-16T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-12-16T03:00:00-05:00" n="633" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3219: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-16T16:00:00+08:00">December 16, 1931—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 16—10:45
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1084. Following from American Consul General at Mukden: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“December 15, 11 p.m. Tsang Shih-yi, Chairman of this Province,
                                    who has been under detention since September 18 at Mukden was
                                    released Sunday and according to reliable information, he was
                                    installed as Governor late this afternoon. In my opinion this
                                    event foreshadows an early attack on Chinchow.</p>
                                <p>Confirmation to follow.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <p>Repeated to Minister at Nanking and Military Attaché at Chinchow.</p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>